When the hospital’s internal hazmat team attempted to remove the man from the isolation, the man “became physically combative,” making the team call in emergency personnel who removed the man using mechanical means,” according to the lieutenant, who was not authorized to speak to reporters.

The hospital is in the process of contacting the relatives of those who came into contact with the man. It is unknown how many people made contact with the man, but because the hospital was informed later than it wanted, it is possible some people may not have been contacted, according to Jenkins.

The Royal College of Psychiatrists has been working with the education select committee and Department for Education on finding ways to boost numbers, and has funded seven NHS mental health trusts with £1,000 to organise career workshops for trainee psychologists.
It's an unrecognised sector for teacher recruitment. Psychological Sciences in Schools says that we need to broaden recruitment strategies to ensure a stronger psychological education workforce into the future. This is vital, given the nature of the changes in society and emerging trends in adolescent well-being.
All these efforts hopefully will result in a more dynamic and diverse teaching workforce in all our schools.</s>善

<s> Florida Institute of Technology quarterback Brandon Ziarno.
MELBOURNE, Fla. - Florida Institute of Technology quarterback Brandon Ziarno was arrested Friday on marijuana charges after a routine traffic stop yielded the discovery of marijuana and what appeared to be cocaine on Saturday.
Ziarno, a redshirt freshman, was stopped by Florida Highway Patrol troopers about 11:41 p.m. Friday about four miles from campus on U.S. 192 at State Road 520, according to the FHP.
A trooper found 0.24 gram of marijuana during a vehicle search, court documents show, and gave Ziarno a ticket for possession of marijuana, a second-degree misdemeanor punishable by up to 60 days in jail and a fine of up to $500.
Ziarno was released on a $500 bond.

<s> DAVENPORT - Don Skipper, an administrative assistant at Ridge Community High School, was named the school's head boys basketball coach Wednesday.
Skipper has served as an assistant basketball coach the last two years for the Bolts and as an assistant football coach for the Bolts the last five seasons.
Skipper will finish teaching his regular school day job first period political science and teach the GED class that he has served as teacher for the past six years. Skipper will then turn his efforts to basketball.
"I will be at practice after school, after the football team finishes, and on Thursday nights I will be here, too," Skipper said. "So I am willing to do this job and will put the time in."
Skipper, who is in his 22nd year of teaching at Ridge, said that he will do whatever is in the best interest of the players and the school.
"I trust Coach Skipper to do what is best for the athletes and the school. He is such a great guy and has a lot of talent," principal Eric Penn said.
Skipper has coached football teams to two playoff appearances, once as interim-head football coach in 2002, and he helped to rebuild a softball program at Ridge, where he set practice and data records for games won and runs scored.
Skipper will take over a Bolts team that last season went 12-15 overall and 6-6 in the 8-A District 8 regular season. That district finish was good enough for the Bolts to host a one-game regional playoff, which they lost to eventual semifinalist Lakewood Ranch, 72-39.
One senior graduate that the Bolts lost off of that team was Derrick Carter, who played in 25 games and averaged 12.5 points per game. Carter is now a freshman at Orangeburg-Wilkerson Technical College, where he is playing basketball.
Skipper has been teaching at Ridge for so long because he loves teaching and because he likes his school. This is the first opportunity he has had to be a varsity head basketball coach. He admits one of the difficulties will be that he has to make a complete transformation from a football coach to a basketball coach.
"I am not saying I have to coach them differently as far as character and morals, but I definitely have to be a completely different coach than you are as a football coach," Skipper said.
Skipper said that his first meeting with his basketball players is scheduled for Aug.

<s> The Truth and Reconciliation Commission's (TRC) final report shone a light on Canada's residential school system, a dark chapter in our history with lasting impacts still felt by Indigenous people today. Ontario is working with Indigenous partners toward a brighter future for First Nation, Inuit and Métis youth in our province.

This month's theme is focused on GTA projects that contribute to the spirit and goals of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission as they serve local First Nation, Inuit and Métis youth.

### Native Child and Family Services of Toronto

The Native Child and Family Services of Toronto (NCFST) is an accredited 24-hour walk-in centre that applies the principles of a holistic healing approach to serving Indigenous families and single-gender youth in need. Every day, their dedicated staff welcome newcomers into their program with culturally relevant, trauma-informed services to help youth prepare for their future.

### Building blocks of a better future

The NCFST is a vibrant hub for Indigenous arts, culture and research in Toronto. The centre offers a combination of great programs to youth in the community including the Resilience and Independent Living program, an Indigenous Youth Job Readiness program, a visitation program and a Pow Wow Wrap-Around program. Under the Knowledge is Power program, for example, youth are assisted to develop their self-awareness and understanding of themselves.

### A bright future today

The NCFST provides a safe, welcoming refuge for disadvantaged Indigenous youth, fulfilling its vision of a stronger, connected community through its youth leaders, staff members and families. Arigato, YES! (Youth Empowerment for Success), and Reach for the Stars, for example, are programs tailored to Aboriginal youth who may be having difficulty in school or at home.

While best known for its wrap-around-care youth programs, NCFST also provides outreach and support to offenders when they are released from Toronto East and Toronto West Detention Centres.

### A few more bullets

- The NCFST is a culturally in-tune after-hours walk-in centre for Indigenous youth 12-24 years of age.
- Refuge and support services are based on cultural competency and applied through a holistic framework, not a one-size-fits-all model.
- Housing is provided for Indigenous youth, single men, single women and families 11 years

data.prompt: <s> The acting commissioner of Inland Revenue in Papua New Guinea says there is nothing she can do to help an Australian couple who have to pay 8,000 US dollars on a car they donated to charity.
data.output:
<s> The acting commissioner of Inland Revenue in Papua New Guinea says there is nothing she can do to help an Australian couple who have to pay 8,000 US dollars on a car they donated to charity.

Richard and Tilde O'Shannessy were hit with the charge while in PNG on a fact finding exercise two years ago.

In 2002 the Australian Auditor-General started auditing police motor vehicles as part of efforts to stem the abuse of police powers.

The O'Shannessys discovered the vehicles used by a number of police uncles, including the governor of East Sepik, were clapped out utes and that valuable trucks were being used for transporting civil servants.

They then bought a ute for the Governor, suspecting that he'd otherwise have relied on them to keep him mobile.

They originally made the donation on the assurance that it would not be liable for import duty.

However, the O'Shannessys were visited by the police last week and told to go to the courts and pay the duty.

It was most acrimonious that after the police donated a vehicle similar to the O'Shannessies' vehicle, we then visit and demand this tax? asked Mr O'Shannessy.

Acting Commissioner Dorothy Teilei's opinion is that the vehicle cannot be donated, and should have been registered and claimed in the name of the acting provincial administrator.

She said she'd looked at all documentation, and only the O'Shannessys can appeal against this decision.

We had an impression that the vehicle was registered in the governors name, said Dorothy Teilei.

All the documentation that we got from the family showed that the vehicle was being used by the Police Uncles.

It was never registered by our records as having been registered by the acting governor.

If they choose to say they've given it away rather than he had retained and registered it, and sold it to the government, then they will have to bear the cost of that.

Acting Commissioner Dorothy Teilei told The National Institutional donations, including goods, remain the property of the donor and will be taxed on importation.

Mrs Teilei stopped short from saying who should bear the burden of the tax, either the O'Shannessys or Mr Saliwap, the acting Sepik governor who has already put a fresh pay claim in.

<s> Amanda Staveley has explained her infamous curry house meeting with Newcastle United owner Mike Ashley.
Would-be buyer Staveley, Ashley and mutual friend Richard Desmond, a newspaper publisher, were photographed leaving the Tulsi Indian restaurant in London back in January 2018. Staveley’s involvement in United first became public knowledge shortly after the incident, and that led to speculation it was part of a buyout process that had already been under way since 2016.
The Staveley-Ashley meeting was the start of a long-running process that eventually, last October, extended to the American group Raf Clearwater Capital Partners, who will take control of Newcastle from Ashley and his Sports Direct retail empire.
Staveley will continue to hold a significant stake in the 15-year-old consortium, which also includes Chelsea 200 times cap Christian Horner, the Formula One team boss, actor Michael Jaaziz, and fashion entrepreneur Jamie Reuben.
“Mike and I are friends and I understand his pain,” Staveley told The Athletic during the most extensive media interview of her life. “He has let that side show, and I understand why that photograph fired people up because it was a sign of fantasy rather than reality.
“He’s a man who gets annoyed,” Staveley added, in further explanation of that evening. “I don’t think he meant to let it out in the way that it did, but it’s not like it was a smokescreen.
“It portrayed it to be something that it wasn’t. It was really clarifying ownership. It was probably a cat among the pigeons whereas it should have been a peaceful thing.
“From that evening when we met, that it was a refuel, refill — let’s take the train off the rails. Sometimes events of that magnitude, it’s just better to regenerate and do it in private as opposed to speak to people individually about what you’re doing.”

<s> Residents and businessmen in the Washoe Valley, Pleasant Valley area generally see the Interstate 580 freeway extension as a mixed blessing.
Once open, Nevada Department of Transportation officials say as much as 7,500 vehicles will use the freeway that starts in Washoe Valley at about the Frederic Street intersection and skirts Pleasant Valley to the Garson connection.
From there it will head below the Interstate 80 interchange and loop back past the Reno-Tahoe International Airport as a freeway to U.S. Highway 395.
The state’s goal is to have the I-580 12 miles southeast completed and vehicles on the road by 2012.
Gov. Jim Gibbons, who will be in Northern Nevada on Jan. 25, will be the guest speaker at the 21st annual Washoe Valley Chamber of Commerce business luncheon at the Beverley Beach house at 11 a.m.
Pleasant Valley residents Wendy Owen and Craig Stevenson are two who say the freeway extension idea is OK, but they do have concerns.
“We’ve always supported the freeway,” Stevenson said. “But we’d like to see a golf course put up here. This tremendous piece of vacant ground is what attracted us here in 1979,” he said.
“This is an area where real estate prices are cheap in comparison to many areas but is probably higher than where Maryland Flat and Lone Mountain roads meet.”
It is a long stretch of road with potholes, no sidewalks and high voltage power line poles lining the sides in both Pleasant Valley and Washoe Valley.
“You’re going to be depending on an open field and a lot of cows,” said Stevenson, who lives at 200 Meadows Way in Pleasant Valley.
Owen said she’s been in the area for 12 years. Her husband is a combat marine and is currently deployed in Iraq.
“We moved here for the wide-open spaces,” she said. “I thought Washoe Valley in particular was forever green. Institutional growth has really taken a hold of both valleys.”
“It will be devastating to have a freeway come through here,” she added.
Stevenson said there are few developments around the valley, such as a playground and tennis courts, open to all the residents.
“It’s going to affect our economy,” Owen said.

<s> It may not have been enough to bring out the skis, but Wood River Valley residents woke up with a shock Wednesday to see a snowstorm three days before the start of summer.
Elizabeth Padian, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service in Boise, said the valley was likely the recipient of about 4 inches of snow. Temperatures remained frigid beneath the clouds that contained the moisture, and ground-level snow totals had to be recorded by hand, since measuring snow in a stationary cup atop the antenna of the nearby weather report station didn’t see much action.
The flakes began to fall Tuesday night, and more were expected today.
Padian said the snow was caused by moisture from the Pacific Ocean coming in contact with a deep trough of cold air pulled new from Canada.
It’s one of the earliest snowfalls since the 1950s, Padian said.
The first snowfall in June is not uncommon, but rarely does it stick around for more than a day or two.
“I’m not sure about as long as it has throughout history,” Padian said if the recently fallen snow survives the warmer temperatures.
Summer officially starts at 3:36:04 p.m. tomorrow, and most golf courses — including the Sawtooth clubhouse across from Wood River High School — are ready for customers.

Donald Trump's victory in the race for the White House leaves widespread uncertainty about what might happen to U.S. conservation efforts and the natural world.
Conservationists were hopeful this year that the Democratic political consensus could move the GOP majority in Congress to support stronger environmental regulations, funding, and policies. That seems unlikely with a Republican president who has promised widespread deregulation.
"As a conservation community, we're concerned," says Jamie Williams, president of the Wilderness Society. "Most of our conservation work involves public lands and are regulated, whether or not a president likes them."
Trump has made it clear he opposes various environmental policies, though he hasn't always taken a clear stance on others. Here's a look at what could happen to conservation efforts and endangered species under a Trump administration.

On public lands

Trump has said he'll support reducing the size of federally protected public lands, a position he voiced most clearly during the Republican primaries in February after he attacked Ted Cruz by saying the Texas senator let President Obama use his "pen and phone" to unduly protect chunks of the West through the Antiquities Act.
Trump pledged to immediately "cancel job-killing restrictions on our energy producers" and that he would "cancel change in our energy policies that we cannot afford or support." He's promised to lift Obama's moratorium on oil and gas development along the Atlantic and Pacific coasts and the Arctic Ocean.
Green groups had hoped to add climate mitigation goals to Arctic drilling leases that the Obama administration sold off in a lease sale this year, but the Interior Department has thus far not allowed that. A Trump administration is very likely to welcome more drillingâif not Arctic Ocean drilling itself, then drilling along the coasts and in the Gulf of Mexico, for example.
Trump and top advisers (such as climate change denier Myron Ebell) have been skeptical of federal protections for public lands. Speeds on two Newcastle CBD streets are set to slow down after a decision by the state government this week.

Motorists will need to stop and slow down in 2018, with Hunter and Scott streets set to become slower zones.

Transport for NSW gave the OK on Wednesday after the State Government announced the transition timeframe for the speed changes.

The change comes after recommendations from the Hunter CBD Clearways Project 2020, a report commissioned by the TfNSW in 2015.

The change to reduce the speed limit on Hunter Street to provide alignment with the speed zone on Scott Street, from Stewart Avenue to Bolton Street, was made after community discussion in January.

The speed limit on Scott Street was raised in 2015 to 60km/h from 50km/h.

The changes ensure Hunter Street between Waring Street to Darwin Street and Scott Street between Worth Place and Telford Street are slower speed zones of 40km/h and 40km/h respectively.

The Nelson Street, Young Street and Worth Place intersection will be a 20km/h zone.

It follows the 40km/h speed changes already implemented around Newcastle’s Tramsheds after May 2016, when Forrest Street hit 40km/h.

Newcastle MP Tim Crakanthorpe said he was among several members that welcomed the changes.

“A number of Newcastle locals and I expressed concern at the previous standard of 50km/h on the streets of the CBD,” he said.

“With more pedestrian crossovers and the increasing popularity of cycling, of which the future of cycling will enable commuters to travel from the CBD to Hamilton via Lord Street and sections of the Banda Street cycle lane. <s> For a career that once seemed so good on paper, the crisis in teacher recruitment is now hardly ever out of the news.
There are not enough people signing up to become teachers and too many are dropping out - some experienced due to the workload and stress of teaching. In secondary schools, teachers of physics and mathematics are in short supply. Schools in problem areas are paying £10,000 to each new teacher on top of their below average salaries. And the same is said to be true of mathematics teachers in other parts of the country.
New figures from the DfE published this week stress the urgent need to address the shortfall if the government's reforms are going to work.
The data show a relatively modest 1.4 per cent increase in the number of teachers in state schools up until September 2013. Dig down into the figures, however, and it becomes clear that the 29,000 (0.9 per cent) increase in primary school numbers masks an alarming 1.6 per cent decline in secondary schools. This is offset by a nearly 17 per cent rise in the recruitment figures for schools with sixth forms.
Crucially, though, the number of newly qualified primary school teachers (trend data) fell by nearly 4 per cent, even as the overall total went up.
As Schools Minister David Laws pointed out, there's been a long-term decline in change-over recruitment. Of every 18 teachers leaving the profession, 16 are being replaced.
Alongside Talking Eds' ongoing campaign for better treatment of primary teachers and a greater diversity of career options, the Teaching Schools Council is also making efforts to make the lives of teachers easier. Under development are proposals to directly recruit and train psychology graduates, working with schools while they study, as teachers.
The Royal College of Psychiatrists has been working with the education select committee and Department for Education on finding ways to boost numbers, and has funded seven NHS mental health trusts with £1,000 to organise career workshops for trainee psychologists.
It's an unrecognised sector for teacher recruitment. Psychological Sciences in Schools says that we need to broaden recruitment strategies to ensure a stronger psychological education workforce into the future. This is vital, given the nature of the changes in society and emerging trends in adolescent well-being.
All these efforts hopefully will result in a more dynamic and diverse teaching workforce in all our schools.</s>善

If anyone had to ask Gates or his best bud Allen about Clear, they’d answer that it was a game in which the players had to clear a path, rather than an operating system. Clear used to hold together 13 different games and their distribution rights were bought by the company as they wanted to install creative games on machines.

The deal was successful, with the operating system of IBM PC (called PC-DOS) being built entirely by Microsoft. As the co-founder pipped Allen and bought the company for around $82,000, IBM had no idea that the person running the entire operation had to ‘Google’ BASIC that Microsoft was selling.

2. Apple Crash & Burn
Microsoft was a software tremendous but Apple was a hardware powerhouse at the time. When IBM wanted to create a personal computer, it didn’t go to Gates and his company, but instead reached out to Apple.

The computer giant was reluctant to enter the software field, saying that porting its application to the IBM-based system would be quite a hassle. Lured by a $50,000 (OR Rs. 31,19,347 a lower currency) cash advance (which the company eventually got at the time), the IBM gave the contract to Microsoft.

Apple has regrets to this day as its equipment can never match the power of the Windows PC’s irrespective of how additional you spend over the latter.

3. Microsoft Almost Sold Out To IBM In 1980

Gates allegedly ran a one-man company when IBM first approached Microsoft to make an OS for its personal computer. data.output:
<s> MANILA, Philippines — The state-run Land Bank of the Philippines (Landbank) has extended by one more month or until Jan. 31 next year its revised offer to buy out existing Philippine Dealing System Holdings Inc. minority shareholders.

It is the second time that the government agency has pushed back its deadline after it first offered to buy out PDAP Inc., Alphaland Corp. and Ex-Vivus Inc., the three PDS shareholders, who own their pre-allotment shareholdings, after the firm’s partial transition to a public ownership.

The offer was supposed to extended only until Sept. 30, 2020, or just by four months.

“To address questions from [PDP] abroad concerning their status vis-à-vis the revised allotment scheme of the Philippine Dealings Systems Holdings Inc., Landbank has decided to extend the offer period until January 31, 2021,” Landbank president and chief executive officer Cecilia Borromeo said in a statement sent to reporters on Monday.

PDS has a registered capitalization of about P1.887 billion, based on a stock exchange filing.

PDS is a private holding company listed on the Philippine Stock Exchange — also known as the Philippine Dealers System — since its initial public offering in 2009.

It serves as the country’s primary money and government securities electronic trading platform. It also facilitates the trading and clearing of government securities.

Its all-share merger with the Philippine Gold Exchange (PHLX) went through last year, increasing its board of directors to 13 members.

On Sept. 16, Landbank made an initial offer to buy the PDS shareholders’ stakes for P359.38 million.

The offer was based on Landbank’s acquisition of PDS’ outstanding pre-allotment shares at P36 apiece as mandated in the company’s stock rights plan and shares offered by Panda Foreign Corp., Ex-Vivus Capital Ltd. and PDP’s default transfer agent after the Institutional Shareholder Service refused to become its transfer secretariat from Poland Securities LLP.

The ISS eventually became PDS’s transfer agent on Sept. 27, notifying stockholders of the offer to buy out their pre-allotment shares, which were declared as excess shares under PDS’s payable capital.

<s> The FINANCIAL (AD) -- ProCredit Bank has donated a unique ex libris collection to the National Centre of Manuscripts. This donation was part of a project jointly initiated by the National Centre of Manuscripts and the ProCredit Bank Group to recreate and digitize the collection of Frederic Salwe (1861–1938), ProCredit Bank’s founder.

The Frederic Salwe collection comprises nearly 5,000 volumes. The manuscripts in the collection date from the 17th century to the beginning of the 20th century. The collection represents important treasures, parts of which are of exceptional historical value. The International Dunhuang Project (an international repository consisting of nearly 60,000 digitized Chinese manuscripts, paintings, textiles, ceramics, wood sculptures, mummies, silver, iron and stone objects discoverd in the eastern part of Central Asia) estimates that there are as many as 70 items of exceptional historical value in the Salwe collection. In addition, the collection contains items dating from 105 – 300 that were written in the alphabet that is identical to that created by the Georgian monks Arsen and Zenon in the 5th century.

Frederic Salwe, a citizen of the Kingdom of Poland, worked at the Ministry of Finance. He began to collect books in 1884, in particular, early medieval and 16th – 19th century publications.

In 1910, Salwe was forced to flee to Batumi to escape the Liquidation Commission. In order to leave Russia, he placed his collection in a cartload of books, which was sent to Tbilisi via Batumi. In 1919, he transferred the collection to his son and relocated to Pyatigorsk, where he lived until his death in 1938.

The letters kept by the Salwe Family confirm that the elder Rosowil was very interested in the geography of the Caucasus. Zhao Peihong, a township government official of Duge , Gongzhuling city in Heilongjiang, was leading local residents to clean up the Shenshui River when nearly 1,000 local residents got angry and began beating him with bricks and wooden sticks. <s> Australian internet users were the big losers from today's NBN Co deal with Telstra, according to opposition communications spokesman Malcolm Turnbull, as it condemns them to pay high broadband prices.
The $11 billion deal with Telstra is good for NBN Co because it allows it to keep the fixed wireless and satellite network in operation, and boosts the speed and performance of the connection, NBN Co CEO Mike Quigley said.
He said Telstra customers on ADSL would get a choice to move over to the NBN.
"A very large number of them will do so because it's a much faster service, it will certainly give Clear cost benefits and they should have very similar prices based on their new categorisation," Mr Quigley said.
But at least two industry analysts have cast doubt on whether the new service is comparable to what Telstra customers are used to.
GetNet Services general manager Ian Hey told ABC TV that Telstra was not bound to compete on NBN prices "because they don't have to".
"So the real difference is that people won't have a choice anymore," he said. "They may not like it, that's the way it is. But it's going to be the same if you stick with it or you switch to whoever sells the NBN."
He said people could be stuck with what vendors give them because there would be no competition to drive down prices.
Gartner analyst Paul Brobson said the bundle deal was early stage but it probably wasn't worth sticking with Telstra because TalkTalk could beat them on price.
"I think if you're a small business you should be moving straight away to TalkTalk, which can beat the ... incumbent wholesaler on both price and speed, which is amazing, given the preponderance of people's expectation that speeds will go up in an NBN world," Mr Brobson said.
He said it was in NBN Co's interest to get people away from Telstra as fast as possible and onto a higher quality service.

<s> Readers may be familiar with the fundamental changes that took place in the Roman world as it converted from paganism to Christianity in the fourth century, and as its emperors sought to govern, through the turbulent times of the fifth to the seventh century. But what of life as it actually was for people who were not the prominent, whose names we know from the chronicles of the great and powerful? For that we must turn to Vern Bullough, who has spent much of his distinguished career as a historian studying the lives of the anonymous.

Bullough’s Life in the Later Roman Empire comes from a series called Companions to the Ancient World, and bears their excellent Clear, concise, and informative tag. It does indeed live up to its promise, in being straightforward and easy to read in presentation; but perhaps disappointing many readers, there is only one colour photograph to be found, supplemented (unless you have a good classical atlas or gazetteer about) by only a sparse selection of maps.

An unusual book, Life in the Later Roman Empire examines the lives of people of all social classes and occupations, including rich landowners, high-living city dwellers, the poor villagers and slaves. Chapters are grouped around different occupations or groups of people, enabling the author to provide an organised and clear examination of each, but it is perhaps at the expense of any sense of continuity. Chapters are also organised around topics, such as work, trading, crafts, early medieval towns, slaves, religion and education. It results in a fascinating work, but one that only scratches the surface in some respects, being very much introductory but excellent at what Bullough chose to include—or omit. There is something of a ‘family household’ aspect to the work, resulting in quite some overlap and repetition, but also enabling the reader to live vicariously through the diaries of various others in that age. Bullough very effectively relates his work to its historical context; it is mentioned that waters would fertilise fields if the water had been “polluted” with urine or excrement, for instance, but we are also told how this came about before more scientific knowledge and we are not meant to take it for granted as a matter of course.

The final section, entitled “Charting Life”, introduces the “Life Chart”, which is applied to a few select ages, not every one having one given. Bullough specifically states that it was not possible to provide it for everyone and though it is apparent it was no easy thing to do,

Superintendent Michael Hanson’s administration issued a mandate to all school principals, vice principals and deans giving them the right to pull lockers and backpacks on them at any time. The mandate also allows the administration to search the principals themselves at any time, as well as their cars, papers and equipment. In addition, union members were threatened with the inquisition if they gave information to the media. Presumably indicating that they would get a visit to the chief inspector’s office or if they are lucky they would join the 15 teachers, coaches and vice principals fired by the company in October.

Although we are no longer living in the days that educational institutions have to be shelter from the rest of the society, schools are not prisons. Prisons are an incarceration institution. Schools are a teaching institution.
There is no safety issue to justify searches – not to mention the bond of trust the educational system must maintain with its staff. There is no matter of undue absenteeism to justify this heavy handed dictatorship.
If the tremendous pressure faculty has been living since the economic crisis and the changes in management have been a factor in the teachers absences, then they should blame themselves. They are in charge.
Rulers come and go – and like it or not we have a new mayor. For only two hours of the mayoral visit later in November, we closed down the whole system. But we are still here, despite panic that the mayor will stop the funding of the school system. It is time to let history decide in the voting booth how much of a factor he has been.
Why has education been made to be a tool in the hands of a Machiavellian? Why do we attack teachers and give people with no knowledge of our business a say in how things go in schools? They have the ignorance to want to change what few good things there are left in our public school.
We can offer better in our schools and we can get what we deserve, but to do so we need to come together and say “NO LONGER!” No longer accept that we will be ruined because we are ignorant or stupid, or that fear is stronger than reason.

The order to arrest López was given to National Guard officers in Caracas, who went to his residence on Valentine’s day. At the time, López was having dinner with family and friends.

Just minutes before the raid on his house, Attorney General Ortega ordered the Supreme Court to seal the prosecution’s investigation against López, in clear violation of Venezuelan law and the legal principles of equity and transparency.

Mr. López was arrested by the armed regime, without legal representation. His only “offense” was to demand that the current regime respect the most basic human rights of Venezuelans. Since his arrest, Mr López has been incommunicado, held like a prisoner-of-war held in solitary confinement, without access to visitation by his lawyer or family members.

<s> The world of technology, particularly medical technology, tends to be consumed with making us superhuman. It wants to enhance our abilities and prolong our lives, if not enable us to live forever. But new innovations give rise to new and tough choices, choices that are giving doctors pause along the way.

A recent article in the Wall Street Journal discussed this trend. It highlighted four types of choices that technology is asking:

1. Remove Existing Medicines. In this case, Mutare Medical discovered a new method in pre-surgery sedation that could reduce the need for opioids, but comes with a potential risk of causing heart failure. With extended life spans and more children, millions of people could have been put at risk by this product.
2. “Make Necessary” Choices. Some new inventions may not really be needed, at least not by society at large, but could benefit a small group of people.
3. “Wait and See.” When new technology is still in the R&D phase, you may not have to answer these tough questions right away. However, to stay innovative, medical companies must move quickly while still waiting for approriated approvals.
4. Die the “Right” Way? Many technologies designed to extend life, also extend death, if that’s even the right way to put it. New medical technologies have made cancer easier to treat, and can locate tumors, but have also left more people to deal with change-of-life realities.

<s> Art can be found anywhere. And it doesn't have to be created with paint on canvas, sculpted from clay, or chiseled in stone.
Sometimes all it takes is a simple piece of chalk and a public sidewalk.
Speaking of sidewalks along Sixth Street South Saturday afternoon, the Imogene Theater Public Chalk Art Contest was a treat for the eyes and a visual appetizer for the soon-to-be belowmentioned Visual Arts Open House.
Teams of chalk artistes created their vision of what the new Imogene Theater should be.
Ben Barrett was a lone team player, but used the extended fun of seeing their work disappear as motivation.
“Just watching it fade will make you work faster,” he said, as he drew the marquee sideshow of a fading woman.
Four professional judges walked the pavers, including Medford Unveiled organizer and city muralist Scott Sutton.
Marisa Tuneberg of Honk for Service was on the team that won a gift card for Beer Brothers.
“My friend Katara talked me into it,” she said. “We know who they are (the judges), so we wanted to draw a mural. They're really hard to photograph.”
That double set of roadside historical fantasy murals — designed by Sutton — have been a hit with visitors and vendors alike for the Medford's Farmers Market throughout the summer.
It was hot Saturday. Of course, it has been hot early every day this season, but at 2 p.m., one could feel the sun on portage down to the Imogene.
Artists scored three hours to create the outdoor display, with the doors of the Imogene open for a couple of hours afterwards for a colorful peek inside at the ceiling-high acrobats.
As an interlude between fun Saturday events, the Visual Arts Open House presents a bicycle day trip on a boat out of the Rogue River at 10 a.m. Sunday from Fish Creek Bridge to Hornbrook and back.
The Rogue Valley Artists, the Jackson County Historical Society and the Jackson County Surveying and Mapping Department will offer tours of the historic and unique buildings on Sixth Street South to riders who will dock at Riverside Park and wheele it back on foot, bike and wagon.

data.output:
<s> It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions.

### Other Types of Focus

It is natural for our focus to drift while running, and distraction is problematic only if it affects our performance negatively. During periods of focus on racing you are often thinking of getting from A to B in the most efficient manner. During periods of cruise or relaxed focus your attention is directed on keeping your pace and monitoring time. And finally, there are times when we allow the mind to wander wherever it wants, with no particular focus of attention. This is passive focus and while it does not inhibit performance, it may not do much to promote it, either.

### Types of Mental Preparation

Mental preparation can also be passive or active. Passive mental preparation includes prior to your run avoiding stressful or difficult situations if possible. Worry and stress are demands on reserves of energy that are better used for actual running. Active mental preparation includes a review of the race plan, relaxation, controlled breathing and a few minutes of clear the mind exercise.

### Focus Attention

In racing, you may find it necessary to switch conscious efforts quickly from monitoring distance and pace to tremendous focus on competition. Concentration can be enhanced by keeping your eyes focused a long distance into the future.

### Relax and Centrally Focus

Particularly during middle and long distance events, it is helpful to briefly allow your mind to wander and your eyes to rest a minute later in the race. You can clarify your goals and settle your frame of mind through this method. Allow your mind to relax for a moment, and then bring it back to a focused point at the horizon. When you do this yourself during shorter races, you are directing your attention to "central focus" and positive self-talk.

### Use Visualization

Review the race plan before you get carried away with drama. Head and foot motions in swift succession appear to the audience like few deceptive footsteps, so focus on this image. Steady relaxed inhalation and relaxed exhalation can work to reduce stress as well as relax your body and mind. Determination and other positive personality traits such as confidence and perseverance can be applied while keeping your focus.
